'''Ianique dos Santos Tavares''' ({{IPA|pt|ja.ˈni.kɨ duʃ ˈsɐ̃.tuʃ ta.ˈva.ɾɨʃ|lang}}; born 20 May 1988), commonly known as '''Stopira''' ({{IPA|kea|sto.ˈpi.ɾɐ|lang}}), is a Cape Verdean professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left-back]] for [[Liga Portugal 2]] club [[S.C.U. Torreense|Torreense]] and the [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde national team]].

He spent most of his career in Hungary with [[Videoton FC Fehérvár|Fehérvár]], having signed for the club in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.anacao.cv/noticia/2023/07/01/internacional-cabo-verdiano-stopira-deixa-o-mol-fehervar-vidi-depois-de-mais-de-uma-decada/|title=Internacional cabo-verdiano Stopira deixa o MOL Fehervar (Vidi) depois de mais de uma década|trans-title=Cape Verdean international Stopira leaves MOL Fehervar (Vidi) after more than one decade|newspaper=[[A Nação]]|language=Portuguese|date=1 July 2023|accessdate=12 September 2023}}</ref>

==Club career==
Stopira was born in [[Praia]]. In 2008, he signed for Portugal's [[C.D. Santa Clara|Santa Clara]] from local side [[Sporting Clube da Praia|Sporting da Praia]], playing just six matches in his [[2008–09 Liga de Honra|first season]] but being first choice in [[2009–10 Liga de Honra|the following]] as the [[Azores]] team competed in the [[Segunda Liga]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/santa-clara/detalhe/laterais-de-regresso|title=Laterais de regresso|trans-title=Full-backs return|newspaper=[[Record (Portuguese newspaper)|Record]]|language=Portuguese|date=8 May 2009|accessdate=2 October 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201007181210/https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/santa-clara/detalhe/laterais-de-regresso|archive-date=7 October 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rtp.pt/acores/sociedade/stopira-diz-que-o-santa-clara-pode-subir-de-divisao-video_11863|title=Stopira diz que o Santa Clara pode subir de divisão (vídeo)|trans-title=Stopira says Santa Clara may promote (video)|publisher=[[RTP Açores]]|first=Paulo|last=Cordeiro|language=Portuguese|date=4 December 2009|accessdate=2 October 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211228221727/https://www.rtp.pt/acores/sociedade/stopira-diz-que-o-santa-clara-pode-subir-de-divisao-video_11863|archive-date=28 December 2021}}</ref>

On 10 July 2010, after a thwarted transfer to [[Primeira Liga]] club [[Vitória S.C.|Vitória de Guimarães]], Stopira signed a four-year contract with [[Deportivo de La Coruña]] in Spain, with 75% of his right being owned by IberSports.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2010/07/09/futbol/equipos/deportivo/1278684725.html?a=f510dc56e93386d426397b7c04533902&t=1290736231|title=El Deportivo ficha al lateral izquierdo Stopira por cuatro temporadas|trans-title=Deportivo sign left-back Stopira for four seasons|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=Spanish|date=9 July 2010|accessdate=26 November 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211228221727/https://www.marca.com/2010/07/09/futbol/equipos/deportivo/1278684725.html?a=f510dc56e93386d426397b7c04533902&t=1290736231|archive-date=28 December 2021}}</ref> He spent his [[2010–11 Segunda División B|only season]], however, with [[Deportivo de La Coruña B|the reserves]] in the [[Segunda División B]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elcorreogallego.es/hemeroteca/lider-toma-medida-deportivo-b-derbi-KCCG601391|title=El líder le toma la medida al Deportivo B en el derbi|trans-title=Leaders measure Deportivo B up in derby|newspaper=[[El Correo Gallego]]|language=Spanish|date=18 October 2010|accessdate=2 October 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211228221730/https://www.elcorreogallego.es/hemeroteca/lider-toma-medida-deportivo-b-derbi-KCCG601391|archive-date=28 December 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/2011/08/12/futbol/equipos/deportivo/1313175142.html|title=El Depor se cansa de Stopira|trans-title=Depor have had enough of Stopira|newspaper=Marca|language=Spanish|date=12 August 2011|accessdate=2 October 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211228221736/https://www.marca.com/2011/08/12/futbol/equipos/deportivo/1313175142.html|archive-date=28 December 2021}}</ref>

Stopira joined newly promoted [[C.D. Feirense|Feirense]] ahead of the [[2011–12 Primeira Liga|2011–12 campaign]], on a one-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/2--liga/feirense/detalhe/lateral-stopira-por-uma-epoca-711954?ref=Pesquisa_Destaques|title=Lateral Stopira por uma época|trans-title=Full-back Stopira for one season|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=13 August 2011|accessdate=2 October 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211228221754/https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/2--liga/feirense/detalhe/lateral-stopira-por-uma-epoca-711954?ref=Pesquisa_Destaques|archive-date=28 December 2021}}</ref> He made his debut in the Portuguese top flight on 20 August 2011, coming on as a late [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 3–1 away loss against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/2011/08/20/desporto/noticia/benfica-derrota-feirense-mas-so-respira-de-alivio-no-fim-1508477|title=Benfica derrota Feirense mas só respira de alívio no fim|trans-title=Benfica beat Feirense but only breathe a sigh of relief in the end|newspaper=[[Público (Portugal)|Público]]|first=Hugo Daniel|last=Sousa|language=Portuguese|date=20 August 2011|accessdate=2 October 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211228221730/https://www.publico.pt/2011/08/20/desporto/noticia/benfica-derrota-feirense-mas-so-respira-de-alivio-no-fim-1508477|archive-date=28 December 2021}}</ref>

In summer 2012, Stopira moved to [[Videoton FC Fehérvár|Fehérvár]] in Hungary. He remained there for 11 years, notably winning the [[2014–15 Nemzeti Bajnokság I|2014–15]] and [[2017–18 Nemzeti Bajnokság I|2017–18 editions]] of the [[Nemzeti Bajnokság I]].<ref name=NB1>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/news/0221-0e908755175e-37172483b04c-1000--videoton-champions-of-hungary-again/?referrer=%2Fmemberassociations%2Fnews%2Fnewsid%3D2242918|title=Videoton champions of Hungary again|publisher=UEFA|first=Matthew|last=Watson-Broughton|date=4 May 2015|accessdate=2 October 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211229002952/https://www.uefa.com/news/0221-0e908755175e-37172483b04c-1000--videoton-champions-of-hungary-again/?referrer=%2Fmemberassociations%2Fnews%2Fnewsid%3D2242918|archive-date=29 December 2021}}</ref><ref name=NB2>{{cite news|url=https://expressodasilhas.cv/desporto/2018/06/17/stopira-no-onze-ideal-do-campeonato-hungaro/58624|title=Stopira no onze ideal do campeonato húngaro|trans-title=Stopira in Hungarian league's all-star XI|newspaper=[[Expresso das Ilhas]]|language=Portuguese|date=17 June 2018|accessdate=2 October 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211228221731/https://expressodasilhas.cv/desporto/2018/06/17/stopira-no-onze-ideal-do-campeonato-hungaro/58624|archive-date=28 December 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://criolosports.com/index.php/criolos-no-estrangeiro/5129-criolos-no-estrangeiro-stopira-atinge-a-marca-de-150-jogos-no-vidi-fc|title=Criolos no estrangeiro: Stopira atinge a marca de 150 jogos no Vidi FC|trans-title=Creoles abroad: Stopira reaches 150 games at Vidi FC|publisher=Criolo Sports|language=Portuguese|date=24 February 2019|accessdate=2 October 2020|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201007052952/http://criolosports.com/index.php/criolos-no-estrangeiro/5129-criolos-no-estrangeiro-stopira-atinge-a-marca-de-150-jogos-no-vidi-fc|archive-date=7 October 2020}}</ref>

Stopira returned to Portugal on 27 July 2024, with the 36-year-old agreeing to a deal at second-tier [[S.C.U. Torreense|Torreense]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/artigo/torreense-anuncia-segundo-reforco-do-dia-stopira-depois-de-talles-wander/17907022|title=Torreense anuncia segundo reforço do dia: Stopira depois de Talles Wander|trans-title=Torreense announce second signing of the day: Stopira after Talles Wander|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|language=Portuguese|date=27 July 2024|accessdate=25 May 2026}}</ref> He scored twice in eight games as the club won the [[2025–26 Taça de Portugal]] for the first major trophy in its 109-year history, from [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalties]]; the first goal was in the second leg of the semi-finals against [[AD Fafe|Fafe]] (2–0 win, 3–1 on aggregate),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnportugal.iol.pt/taca-portugal/torreense/taca-torreense-fafe-2-0-cronica|title=Taça: Torreense-Fafe, 2–0 (crónica)|trans-title=Cup: Torreense-Fafe, 2–0 (report)|publisher=[[CNN Portugal]]|first=Diogo|last=Marques|language=Portuguese|date=23 April 2026|accessdate=25 May 2026}}</ref> and the second in the [[2026 Taça de Portugal final|decisive match]] to help defeat holders [[Sporting CP]] 2–1.<ref name=PC>{{cite web|url=https://portugoal.net/club-news/5780-sporting-1-2-torreense-extra-time-joy-for-torreense-who-make-history-in-portuguese-cup-final|title=Sporting 1–2 Torreense: extra time joy for Torreense who make history in Portuguese Cup final|publisher=PortuGOAL|first=Tom|last=Kundert|date=24 May 2026|accessdate=24 May 2026}}</ref>

==International career==
Stopira received his first call-up to the [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde national team]] in May 2008, for a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] with [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] and a [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|qualifier]] against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=772955/|title=Foreign contingent boost Cape Verde|publisher=FIFA|date=21 May 2008|accessdate=28 June 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508222918/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=772955/|archive-date=8 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=865506/|title=Pele called in for Cape Verde|publisher=FIFA|date=30 May 2008|accessdate=28 June 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508222810/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=865506/|archive-date=8 May 2014}}</ref> He was an unused substitute in the first two qualifying matches, and made his competitive debut against [[Mauritius national football team|Mauritius]] on 22 June of that year, replacing [[Nando (footballer, born 1978)|Nando]] in the dying minutes.

On 24 May 2010, Stopira appeared in a friendly in [[Covilhã]] with [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] – who were preparing for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup]] in South Africa – playing the entire match as the minnows (ranked 117th) managed a 0–0 draw.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/2010-05-24-2037303516_x.htm|title=Portugal held to 0–0 draw by Cape Verde|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=24 May 2010|accessdate=28 June 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623060630/http://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/2010-05-24-2037303516_x.htm|archive-date=23 June 2011}}</ref> He also won the [[2009 Lusofonia Games]] with the under-21 team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noticias.sapo.cv/info/artigo/1065853.html|title=Futebol: Santa Clara dificulta transferência de Stopira para Guimarães|trans-title=Football: Santa Clara make Stopira transfer to Guimarães difficult|publisher=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|first=Evandro|last=Delgado|language=Portuguese|date=18 May 2010|accessdate=28 June 2010|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303232027/http://noticias.sapo.cv/info/artigo/1065853.html|archive-date=3 March 2016}}</ref>

In May 2026, Stopira was named in Cape Verde's [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] squad for [[2026 FIFA World Cup|that year's World Cup]], in their first-ever participation in [[FIFA World Cup|the tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c74r18j8kwno|title=Shamrock's Lopes makes Cape Verde's World Cup squad|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|first=Lorraine|last=McKenna|date=18 May 2026|accessdate=19 May 2026}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Stopira received his nickname in honour of former [[France national football team|French]] international [[Yannick Stopyra]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/v--guimaraes/detalhe/stopira-e-um-salto-na-minha-carreira|title=Stopira: "É um salto na minha carreira"|trans-title=Stopira: "This is a leap in my career"|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=24 May 2010|accessdate=1 October 2020}}</ref> In December 2019, he acquired [[Hungarian nationality law|Hungarian citizenship]] via [[naturalization]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rangado.24.hu/magyar_foci/2019/12/09/stopira-magyar-allampolgar/|title=Fehérvár: Stopira is magyar állampolgár lett|trans-title=Fehérvár: Stopira also became a Hungarian citizen|publisher=24.hu|language=Hungarian|date=9 December 2019|accessdate=1 October 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211228075729/https://rangado.24.hu/magyar_foci/2019/12/09/stopira-magyar-allampolgar/|archive-date=28 December 2021}}</ref>

